          <p style="line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:20px;">Start with licensing: every pest control technician working on your property must hold a valid Utah Department of Agriculture and Food (UDAF) license. Ask for the license number and verify it. Next, confirm they carry liability insurance — if a treatment damages your property or a chemical exposure occurs, you need coverage.</p>
          <p style="line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:20px;">Ask about their guarantee. A reputable company stands behind its work. Wernex, for example, provides a 100% satisfaction guarantee with free re-service within 30 days if pests return. No questions asked.</p>
          <p style="line-height:1.8;">Finally, ask about their experience with Southern Utah-specific pests. Bark scorpions, subterranean termites, and desert rodents require different approaches than the pests found in Salt Lake City or northern Utah. A company that understands Washington County's pest ecology will deliver better results than a generic national franchise.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
